(42, 20, 45, 54, 5, 20, 20, 'in the audience of all the people', 'Public Rebuke and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of public accountability in both passages. Luke 20:45 mentions speaking ''in the audience of all the people,'' while 1 Timothy 5:20 emphasizes rebuking ''before all'' to instill fear in others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 46, 41, 12, 38, 39, NULL, 'Scribes'' Love for Status', 'Both passages emphasize the scribes'' desire for status and recognition, highlighting their love for long robes, greetings in marketplaces, and prominent seating at feasts. This connection illustrates a shared critique of their behavior.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 46, 42, 11, 43, 43, 'the highest seats in the synagogues', 'Connection of Scribes and Pharisees', 'Both passages emphasize the desire for ''uppermost seats'' and public recognition. This connection highlights the shared criticism of religious leaders who seek status and honor in social settings.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 46, 42, 14, 7, 7, 'the chief rooms at feasts', 'Connection of Scribes and Seating', 'Both passages emphasize the desire for ''chief rooms'' and the prominence associated with social status. The scribes in Luke 20:46 are criticized for their love of high positions, which is mirrored in Luke 14:7 where guests seek the best seats.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 46, 40, 16, 6, 6, 'Beware of the scribes', 'Warning Against Religious Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the need to beware of religious leaders who seek status and influence. Luke warns against the scribes'' desire for recognition, while Matthew cautions against the teachings of the Pharisees and Sadducees, suggesting a shared concern about their influence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 46, 40, 23, 5, 7, 'love greetings in the markets', 'Scribes'' Desire for Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the scribes'' desire for public recognition and status. They highlight similar behaviors, such as seeking prominent seats and greetings in public spaces.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 46, 50, 2, 3, 5, 'love greetings in the markets', 'Contrast in Attitudes Toward Status', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the scribes'' desire for status and the call in Philippians to act in lowliness of mind. Both passages emphasize the importance of humility and valuing others over oneself.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 46, 20, 29, 23, 23, 'love greetings in the markets', 'Pride and Humility in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of pride and its consequences. In Luke 20:46, the scribes'' desire for status reflects pride, while Proverbs 29:23 contrasts this by stating that pride brings one low, emphasizing the value of humility.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 47, 41, 12, 40, 40, 'devour widows’ houses', 'Connection of Condemnation for Hypocrisy', 'Both passages emphasize the condemnation of those who exploit the vulnerable, specifically widows, while pretending to be pious through long prayers. The similar phrasing regarding ''devour widows’ houses'' and ''long prayers'' highlights a shared theme of hypocrisy and moral failure.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 47, 59, 3, 1, 1, 'greater damnation', 'Condemnation of Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of receiving greater condemnation for those in positions of authority. Luke 20:47 warns about the consequences for those who exploit the vulnerable, while James 3:1 cautions against many masters, indicating a similar accountability.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 47, 42, 12, 1, 1, 'devour widows’ houses', 'Hypocrisy of the Pharisees', 'Both passages emphasize the hypocrisy of the Pharisees, with Luke 20:47 highlighting their exploitation of widows and Luke 12:1 warning against their deceptive practices. This connection highlights the moral corruption present in their actions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 47, 42, 12, 47, 48, NULL, 'Accountability for Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of one''s actions and the greater accountability that comes with knowledge and power. The warning in Luke 20:47 about greater damnation for those who exploit others parallels the idea in Luke 12:47-48 that those who know their lord''s will are held to a higher standard.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 47, 56, 1, 16, 16, 'the same shall receive greater damnation', 'Condemnation of Hypocritical Behavior', 'This connection highlights the condemnation of those who outwardly profess faith but engage in deceitful and harmful actions. Both passages emphasize the discrepancy between profession and practice, leading to greater judgment.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 47, 23, 10, 2, 2, 'devour widows’ houses', 'Exploitation of Widows and Poor', 'Both passages emphasize the exploitation of widows and the needy. Luke 20:47 mentions those who ''devour widows’ houses,'' while Isaiah 10:2 states that ''widows may be their prey.'' This connection highlights a common theme of injustice against vulnerable individuals.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 47, 24, 7, 6, 10, 'devour widows’ houses', 'Oppression of the Vulnerable', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of protecting the widow and the consequences of exploiting them. Luke 20:47 warns against devouring widows'' houses, while Jeremiah 7:6-10 calls for not oppressing widows and others. This connection highlights a shared theme of justice for the vulnerable.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 1, 41, 12, 41, 44, 'casting their gifts into the treasury', 'Observation of Treasury Contributions', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus observing how people cast money into the treasury. They highlight the contrast between the rich who give much and the poor widow who gives all she has.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 1, 43, 8, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Treasury References', 'This connection highlights the setting of both passages in the treasury, emphasizing the significance of the location in Jesus'' teachings. Both passages involve the act of giving and teaching within the temple context.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 1, 14, 36, 18, 18, NULL, 'Connection of Treasures and Gifts', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''treasures'' related to the house of God. In Luke, the rich men are contributing gifts, while in 2 Chronicles, the treasures of the house of God are taken to Babylon, highlighting the significance of these offerings.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 1, 40, 27, 6, 6, 'into the treasury', 'Connection of Treasury and Gifts', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the treasury. In Luke, the rich men cast gifts into the treasury, while in Matthew, the chief priests discuss the lawfulness of putting money into the treasury.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 1, 16, 13, 13, 13, 'treasury', 'Treasury and Faithfulness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of treasuries and the act of giving. Both passages emphasize the importance of those who manage and distribute resources faithfully.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 1, 6, 6, 19, 19, 'treasury', 'Treasury of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a treasury dedicated to the Lord. In Luke, the rich men cast their gifts into the treasury, while in Joshua, the items are consecrated to come into the treasury of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 1, 12, 24, 13, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Treasures and Giving', 'This connection highlights the theme of treasures associated with both the rich men giving in the temple and the treasures taken from the house of the Lord. Both passages emphasize the significance of wealth and its relation to sacred spaces.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 2, 41, 12, 42, 42, 'a certain poor widow casting in thither two mites', 'Connection of Widow''s Offering', 'Both passages emphasize a certain poor widow casting in two mites. This highlights the significance of her humble contribution in the context of giving.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 3, 47, 8, 12, 12, 'this poor widow hath cast in more', 'Value of Giving in Faith', 'This connection highlights the principle of sacrificial giving. Both passages emphasize that the value of a gift is determined by the willingness and heart behind it, rather than the amount given.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 3, 44, 10, 34, 34, 'Of a truth', 'Value of the Poor', 'This connection highlights the theme of value in God''s eyes, where the poor widow''s offering is deemed greater than the rich, paralleling Peter''s realization that God values all individuals equally, regardless of status. Both passages emphasize the intrinsic worth of those who may be overlooked by society.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 3, 47, 8, 2, 3, 'this poor widow hath cast in more', 'Generosity in Poverty', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of giving despite poverty. The widow''s offering in Luke illustrates sacrificial giving, while the Macedonian churches in 2 Corinthians demonstrate generosity that exceeds their ability, highlighting the richness of their liberality.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 3, 2, 35, 21, 29, 'this poor widow hath cast in more than they all', 'Willingness in Offerings', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of willingness in giving. The widow''s offering in Luke reflects the spirit of generosity seen in the Israelites'' offerings in Exodus, where each person contributed according to their heart''s stirring.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 3, 41, 12, 43, 44, 'this poor widow hath cast in more', 'Connection of Widow''s Offering', 'Both passages emphasize the poor widow''s offering as greater than others. They highlight her sacrificial giving, contrasting her contribution with those who gave from abundance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 21, 3, 41, 14, 8, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Generosity and Sacrifice', 'This connection highlights the theme of sacrificial giving. Both passages emphasize the value of actions done out of love and devotion, regardless of material wealth.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
